<HL>
   Steel Production Rose
   By 0.7% Last Week
</HL>
<DATE>
08/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<IN>
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Raw-steel production by the nation's mills
increased 0.7% last week to 1,858,000 tons from 1,845,000
tons the previous week, the American Iron and Steel Institute
said.
   Last week's output fell 0.2% from 1,862,000 tons a year
earlier. The industry used 83.3% of its capability last week,
compared with 82.7% the previous week and 83.8% a year ago.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The American Iron and Steel Institute reported:
                                                                                                       

                                     Net tons   Capability
                                     produced   utilization
                                                                                                       

   Week to Aug. 4 ................  1,858,000      83.3%
   Week to July 28 ...............  1,845,000      82.7%
   Year to date .................. 58,462,000      84.5%
   Year earlier to date .......... 60,365,000      88.0%
                                                                                                       

   The capability utilization rate is a calculation designed
to indicate at what percent of its production capability the
industry is operating in a given week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900807-0127
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900807-0127.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Merrill Lynch Said
   To Be Seeking
   Buyer for Unit
   ----
   By Mitchell Pacelle
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21
</SO>
<CO>
   MER
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. is searching for a buyer for Merrill
Lynch, Hubbard Inc., its real estate investment and
syndication unit, according to two people familiar with the
company's efforts.
   Hubbard, which has about 105 employees, manages
approximately $1.5 billion of commercial and residential real
estate for more than 230,000 investors in 10 partnerships.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Lynch has been retreating to its core of
securities brokerage and investment banking businesses for
more than a year. The Hubbard unit has been for sale since
early this year, according to people familiar with the
efforts. But turmoil in the market for real estate limited
partnerships has reduced the number of potential buyers.
   Two syndicators who remain strong -- Atlanta-based
Equitable Real Estate Investment Management Inc., and
Chicago-based JMB Realty -- are considering the acquisition
of Hubbard, according to people familiar with Merrill's
efforts.
   "Hubbard is under constant review, but no decision to sell
it has been made as of this date," said Merrill spokesman
William Clark, who would not comment on whether the unit is
for sale.
   Merrill officials decline to disclose how much they are
asking for the unit, as do officials from both Equitable and
JMB Realty.
   Between 1981 and 1987, Hubbard raised $1.7 billion dollars
to purchase real estate through a series of six MLH Income
Realty Partnerships. Hubbard made cash-based acquisitions of
commercial properties with strong cash flows and good
potentials for appreciation, according to Larry Kay, who
follows Hubbard for Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
   After flourishing in the mid-1980s, the market for real
estate limited partnerships was crippled by the 1986 Tax
Reform Act. Previously, investors were able to write off
losses from real esate limited partnerships against ordinary
income. After 1986, the losses could only be written off
against passive income, such as income from other limited
partnerships. The collapse of real estate markets in the
South, Southwest, and Northeast also stemmed the flow of
investors seeking to capitalize on runaway real estate
prices.
   The deterioration of the market threw Integrated Resources
Inc. in New York and Southmark Corp. of Dallas, two
syndicators that relied heavily on investors seeking tax
shelters, into bankruptcy-court proceedings. Unlike Hubbard,
these two syndicators had highly leveraged portfolios.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
