<HL>
   Marketing Brief -- Vestron Inc.:
   Tentative Pact on Purchase
   By Live Entertainment Set
</HL>
<DATE>
08/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   VV LVE CRC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Vestron Inc. said it tentatively agreed to be acquired by
Live Entertainment Inc. and will seek the approval of holders
of about $158 million in Vestron debt.
   The proposed acquisition marks the final winding down of
Vestron, a video distributor and movie maker whose fortunes
had soared with the hit movie "Dirty Dancing" only three
years ago. The company ran into debt problems last year after
the videotape market became glutted, as bids for movie rights
skyrocketed, and after $100 million in promised financing for
the company collapsed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Terms of the proposed sale weren't disclosed. Vestron's
chairman, Austin Furst, who holds about 85% of Vestron's
common shares, couldn't be reached for comment.
   It wasn't immediately clear whether Vestron, based in
Stamford, Conn., would operate as a separate subsidiary of
Live Entertainment, which is based in Van Nuys, Calif., and
is 48%-owned by Carolco Pictures Inc. Vestron in the past
year has sold overseas video-distribution operations and a
U.S. TV-programming unit. Its remaining assets include
distribution rights to 1,500 titles and the film-sequel
rights to "Dirty Dancing."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900807-0020
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900807-0020.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology Brief -- Tandy Corp.:
   Electronics Retailer Unveils
   6-Pound Portable Computer
</HL>
<DATE>
08/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   TAN
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   Tandy Corp. introduced a six-pound portable computer,
equipped with hard-disk and floppy-disk drives and priced at
$1,999, the first in what could become a deluge of "notebook"
computers.
   The Tandy 1500HD is lighter and more powerful than the
1100FD model, introduced in September by the Fort Worth,
Tex.-based electronics retailer. Since then, the market for
notebook computers, slim enough to slip into a briefcase but
powerful enough to run popular business software, has become
crowded and competitive.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Tandy 1500HD raises the competitive stakes, analysts
believe. "It's a pretty aggressive price," said Liz Buyer, a
vice president of Needham &amp; Co.
   The computer comes equipped with a 20-megabyte hard-disk
drive and a 1.44 megabyte floppy drive. It uses a NEC V-20
microprocessor, a faster version of the Intel 8086 chip.
   Tandy said the computer will be available in Radio Shack
stores in September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
