<HL>
   Crude Prices Hit
   Highest Levels
   In Over 4 Years
   ---
   Many Analysts Say Oil Costs
   May Rise Much Further
   If Gulf Tensions Escalate
   ----
   By James Tanner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   Petroleum prices exploded on crisis buying to the highest
levels in more than four years.
   Prices surged $3 to $4 a barrel around the world as Iraqi
troops occupying Kuwait appeared to be digging in on Saudi
Arabia's border.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the U.S., crude oil futures topped $28 a barrel, a
level of domestic petroleum prices not seen since before the
oil-price collapse of early 1986.
   Some oil analysts turned cautious, suggesting prices may
be near their peaks after the run-up of more than $10 a
barrel in recent weeks. But most said that if Middle East
tensions continued to escalate, prices could still go far
higher to close in on the records of the early 1980s of $30
to $40 a barrel.
   "It's a free-for-all," said Michael Rothman, vice
president and a senior energy analyst at Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets. "People are concerned not only about the
loss of Iraqi and Kuwaiti oil but fear that Saudi Arabia's
production may also be in jeopardy."
   Global sanctions continued to tighten against President
Saddam Hussein of Iraq. An embargo threatened to choke off
from world oil supplies some four million barrels a day of
crude oil and petroleum products that Iraq and Kuwait had
been exporting.
   While industry officials were skeptical that all the oil
flowing from Iraq and Kuwait could be cut off, there were
indications yesterday that the embargo had begun to work.
Because some of the tankers that were to pick up Iraqi oil at
the Mediterranean port of Ceyhan, Turkey, sailed away after
the embargo began, Iraq stopped pumping crude through one of
its pipelines there. It also reduced the flow of oil through
another pipeline across Turkey.
   These developments, combined with the rapid rise in oil
prices, also pushed the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries further into disarray. Over the weekend, some of
the OPEC oil ministers had indicated they might hold an
emergency session to try to take steps to slow the run-up in
oil prices.
   The idea would be for some of those with spare producing
capacity to begin producing above the quotas that have been
so controversial until oil prices began rising. And some of
the countries that want a more moderate approach to pricing
to protect their market shares of the future are understood
to have begun stepping up their output.
   Yesterday, however, OPEC's Vienna headquarters reported
that it hadn't been advised of any requests for an emergency
meeting. "OPEC is not doing anything," an official said,
"except to wait and see."
   Several oil ministers called, meanwhile, for adherence to
the production quotas that were re-established last month.
The July agreement had set a ceiling of 22.5 million barrels
a day for total OPEC production and brought the United Arab
Emirates, a chronic overproducer, back into the fold with a
higher quota.
   It's generally assumed the July agreement was nullified by
the fact that one Persian Gulf member of OPEC, Iraq, invaded
and occupied another gulf member, Kuwait. But Mana Said
Otaiba, the Emirates' oil minister, was among several
ministers yesterday urging continued compliance with the
agreement. He sent a message to Sadek Boussena, Algeria's oil
minister and OPEC president, calling on all member states not
to exceed their quotas "under the current circumstances in
the {Persian Gulf} region."
   Immediate oil shortages aren't expected even if Iraqi and
Kuwaiti crudes are cut off completely by embargoes or by
blockades. J. Robinson West, president of Petroleum Finance
Co., noted that world oil inventories are at a nine-year high
and that demand for OPEC oil is less than the 22.5 million
barrels a day allowed under the production ceiling. But he
suggested major differences between the "actual structure of
the market and the psychology of the market."
   Whether warranted or not, oil prices leaped record amounts
yesterday. Some U.S. oil companies increased their field
postings, what their refineries are paying, for West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark crude, by a record $3.50 a barrel
to $26.50. On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the futures
price of a WTI-like crude for September delivery jumped a
record $3.56 to settle at $28.05 a barrel.
   "What was a surplus in oil inventories only a week ago
suddenly is considered balance today," said William H. Brown
III, international oil analyst at Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co.
   According to studies by Mr. Brown, a two-month disruption
in Iraq and Kuwait exports would carry WTI to a new peak of
$29 a barrel even if other nations such as Saudi Arabia
produce more oil to fill the gap. If others in OPEC don't try
to make up the lost supplies, "you are talking $37 plus for
WTI," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900807-0013
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900807-0013.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
08/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE SECURITY COUNCIL IMPOSED a global trade embargo on
Iraq.
   The U.N. panel's 13-0 vote, provoked by the invasion of
Kuwait, was the organization's first total trade and arms
boycott in 23 years. To ensure its success, the U.S. is
considering an international naval blockade against Baghdad.
"These sanctions will be enforced, no matter what it takes,"
Bush said. In a bid to stop the flow of Iraqi oil, Baker
prepared to go to Turkey for talks. But Iraq shut one of its
pipelines in Turkey and gave arms to civilians in Baghdad.
The U.S. said 28 Americans were believed to be among a group
Iraqis seized in Kuwait.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Cheney held talks with Saudi leaders in
Jiddah, and the White House said "the defense of Saudi Arabia
is of paramount concern."
   ---
   BHUTTO WAS DISMISSED and her 20-month Pakistani government
dissolved.
   Saying the Bhutto government was ineffective and corrupt,
President Ishaq Khan dismissed the premier, dissolved the
National Assembly and declared a state of emergency. He
appointed Bhutto's political rival Jatoi as caretaker prime
minister and scheduled elections for Oct. 24. The Pakistan
army took over the television station and phone exchanges,
and spread troops through the capital.
   Bhutto, the first woman leader of an Islamic country, said
that the corruption allegations against her government were
the product of a "slander campaign."
   ---
   THE ANC HALTED its 30-year armed struggle against the
Pretoria government.
   After a day of talks with officials of South Africa's
white-minority government, the African National Congress
announced the suspension, clearing the way for the start of
negotiations over a new constitution based on black-white
power sharing. Mandela said his group's infiltration of
trained guerrillas and weapons into South Africa would stop
immediately, as would all military activities inside the
country.
   Pretoria said it would begin a phased release of political
prisoners and would grant indemnity to 20,000 ANC exiles so
they can return to South Africa.
   ---
   Liberian rebels seized an American and 13 or 14 other
foreigners in Monrovia. The U.S. said the group was taken to
the headquarters of Prince Johnson, who leads one of two
rival factions fighting to oust President Doe. There was no
indication whether members of the group had been harmed.
                                                                                                       

   Five West African leaders agreed to send troops into
Liberia to impose a cease-fire in the civil war. The task
force reportedly would comprise troops from Nigeria, Ghana,
Guinea, Sierra Leone and Gambia.
   ---
   The Social Democrats demanded the two Germanys unite by
Sept. 15, saying East Germany's economic conditions are
"catastrophic." The party, the second-largest in both German
states, set the deadline after a joint meeting. Ruling
parties of the two Germanys have said unity must wait for a
pan-German vote that should be held Oct. 14.
   ---
   The Soviet Union said U.S. proposals for a 25% reduction
in American armed forces within five years were "an important
step forward." But a foreign ministry spokesman in Moscow
added that Washington could do more by cutting naval forces
and trimming expenditures on costly programs such as the B-2
Stealth bomber.
   ---
   Salvage crews cleaned the tanks of a crippled oil barge
off Galveston, Texas, so that it could be cut up and the
Houston Ship Channel reopened to traffic. Officials didn't
know how long it would take to break up the barge, crippled
in a collision that left 700,000 gallons of oil in Galveston
Bay.
   ---
   The U.S. and Vietnam held their first formal talks on
Cambodia in a step toward possible normalization of
relations. The agenda of the talks wasn't disclosed. The
meeting in New York followed a U.S. decision July 18 to
withdraw diplomatic recognition from the anti-Vietnamese
Cambodian resistance coalition dominated by the Khmer Rouge.
   ---
   The FDA approved a new treatment for a lung ailment that
kills some 5,000 premature infants each year in the U.S. The
federal agency's action cleared the sale of a drug that is
manufactured by Burroughs Wellcome for treating respiratory
distress syndrome, which is a breathing difficulty resulting
from immature lungs.
   ---
   A judge in Los Angeles dismissed Peggy McMartin Buckey's
$1 million civil suit alleging malicious prosecution in the
seven-year McMartin Pre-School molestation trial that ended
with her acquittal. Her attorney said he would appeal the
ruling.
</TEXT>
