<HL>
   Monday's Markets:
   Stocks, Bonds Plunge on Middle East, Oil Fears
   ---
   Dow Industrials Fall 93.31;
   Inflation Worries Lead
   To Treasury Issue Rout
   ----
   By Tom Herman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   Stocks and bonds plunged around the world as investors
took flight from heightened risks caused by Middle East
turmoil and surging oil prices.
   With recession fears growing rapidly, the Dow Jones
Industrial Average tumbled 93.31 points in heavy trading to
close at 2716.34. That was the biggest one-day drop since
October's "minicrash." Stock prices also fell sharply in
Japan, which imports nearly all its oil, as well as in
Britain, Germany, Spain, and France.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Yesterday's financial markets were "tumultuous and scary,"
said John Rosenthal, senior partner at Silberberg, Rosenthal
&amp; Co., a New York brokerage firm. However, "It absolutely
didn't feel like Oct. 19 or 20, 1987. At no time was there
panic selling," said Donald Stone, vice chairman of the New
York Stock Exchange and senior partner at Lasker, Stone and
Stern. "But it felt like the market was under real pressure."
   So were bonds. Fearing that higher oil prices will sharply
accelerate inflation, investors bailed out of long-term
bonds. In the biggest rout in about three years, Treasury
bond prices plummeted 2 5/8 points, or $26.25 for each $1,000
face amount. The yield on 30-year Treasury bonds climbed to
8.80% from 8.56% late Friday. Bond yields also jumped in most
major international markets, including Britain, Japan and
Germany.
   Many "junk" bonds -- high-yielding, high-risk bonds issued
by companies with low credit ratings or no ratings at all --
also were hard hit. Investors fear a recession could
undermine companies with heavy debt burdens.
   Even municipal bonds, typically among the quietest, least
volatile securities, were dragged into the bond market's
descent. Prices of many tax-free bond issues tumbled as much
as 1 1/2 points.
   All major financial markets vibrated to the same tune:
"Fear of a wider Middle East conflagration," said Robert
Hormats, vice chairman of Goldman Sachs International.
"People are afraid of an attack on Saudi Arabia, which would
probably cause much greater disruption of oil flows," said
Mr. Hormats, a former State Department official. "The
consequences would be shattering."
   Investors seeking a financial bomb shelter turned for
protection to short-term Treasury bills, noted for safety.
Individual investors flooded the Treasury with a huge wave of
orders at yesterday's regular weekly government auction of
short-term bills. Rates fell sharply from a week earlier on
both three-month and six-month Treasury bills.
   Investors also rushed to buy gold, stocks of precious
metals and mining companies, as well as shares of oil
producers and several defense contractors.
   But surging interest rates hammered utility stocks.
Utilities are heavy borrowers, and their stock prices are
very sensitive to interest rate changes. The Dow Jones
Utility Average fell 4.78 points to 204.92.
   Rising oil prices pummeled transportation stocks,
especially trucking and airline issues. The Dow Jones
Transportation Average sank 58.76 to 980.29.
   Smaller stocks tended to be hurt more than big ones. While
the Dow industrials fell 3.3%, the Nasdaq composite index of
over-the-counter stocks plunged 4.2%.
   The Big Board held a hastily arranged news conference to
assure investors that the stock market was humming along just
fine. Asked why more than a dozen major stocks didn't open
for trading at the 9:30 a.m. EDT opening bell, Richard
Torrenzano, an exchange spokesman, said it was more important
that 28 of the 30 stocks in the Dow Jones industrials opened
within a half hour. "That's quite good" under the
circumstances, he said.
   In foreign-exchange trading, the dollar fell sharply
against most major currencies, although it rose slightly
against the yen. Traders said worries that higher oil prices
will further slow an already limping U.S. economy, coupled
with concern about tumbling U.S. bond and stock prices,
overshadowed the dollar's status as a safe-haven investment.
The dollar also was hurt by worries that higher oil prices
will mean even bigger U.S. budget and trade deficits.
   At one point yesterday, the dollar dropped to just above
its record post-World War II low against the German mark of
1.5615 marks, set in January 1988.
   Some traders had hoped that the Federal Reserve would try
to restore calm to the shaky markets and bolster the sagging
U.S. economy by easing credit another notch. But the Fed
didn't take any such action.
   Fed officials face a tough choice. If they drive down
short-term rates to calm market jitters, they run a large
risk of intensifying inflation fears, which could further
undermine the markets.
   The bond market slump comes at a bad time for the U.S.
government. This week, the Treasury is scheduled to sell a
record $32.25 billion of new notes and bonds to pay the
government's bills. The bond market's sudden sinking spell
means the Treasury will have to pay substantially higher
interest rates to attract investors.
   Some traders think the Treasury will have to offer yields
of nearly 9% on the 30-year bonds tentatively slated for sale
Thursday, up from 8.5% since Friday and the highest since
early spring. Today, the Treasury is scheduled to sell new
three-year notes. Bond specialists estimate the notes will be
sold at an average annual yield of about 8% to 8 1/8%, up
from 7.94% on Friday.
   In major markets:
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices tumbled. Declining Big Board stocks
outnumbered advancing issues by 1,530 to 255.
                                                                                                       

   Bond prices fell sharply. The Treasury's 30-year bonds
fell to 99 10/32 from 101 30/32 Friday.
                                                                                                       

   The dollar slumped against most major currencies. In late
New York trading yesterday, the dollar fell to 1.5765 German
marks from 1.5935 marks late Friday. But the dollar was
quoted at 150.32 Japanese yen, up from 149.99.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900807-0006
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900807-0006.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   The Mideast Crisis:
   Insurers Face Huge Risk in Persian Gulf;
   Coverage, if Available, May Get Costlier
   ----
   By Beatrice E. Garcia and Craig Forman
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/07/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
PETROLEUM (PET)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
MARINE TRANSPORTATION (MAR)
</IN>
<LP>
   Government export insurers and some private insurers could
have billions of dollars at risk in the Persian Gulf if
hostilities in the region escalate further. In addition,
companies seeking to do business there may have to pay dearly
for insurance coverage, if it's still available.
   Insurance rates for shipping through the Persian Gulf have
risen sharply since Iraq's invasion of Kuwait last Thursday.
Lloyd's of London, a big British insurance marketer, has led
a world-wide round of price increases for certain oil and
marine coverage. Lloyd's also has posted a war-risk premium
on Persian Gulf shipping for the first time since the
Iran-Iraq war.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Aside from shipping, companies already doing business in
the region probably won't see their premiums shoot up
immediately. But if the Gulf conflict continues for several
months, their insurance costs could be affected in January,
when insurance renewals are typically negotiated.
   The market for political-risk coverage in Iraq and Kuwait
has virtually shut down, brokers and underwriters said. "I
wouldn't have the audacity to ask an underwriter for a
quote," said Anthony Palmer, a managing director of Berry
Palmer &amp; Lyle, Ltd., a Lloyd's of London broker that
specializes in political-risk coverage.
   Yet, depending on the project and amount of risk involved,
underwriters might still be willing to provide political-risk
coverage for companies seeking business in Saudi Arabia and
other parts of the region, said Ken Horne, a vice president
who heads the political-risk department for Johnson &amp;
Higgins, a New York-based broker.
   Mr. Horne noted that when Chinese army tanks moved to
crush the student protest in Beijing's Tiananmen Square in
June last year, rates for political-risk coverage in China
virtually doubled overnight. They stabilized within about a
month after the crisis.
   "I wouldn't rule out a 100% rate increase versus {levels
seen} two weeks ago" for political-risk coverage in the
Persian Gulf region, with rates leveling off after a while,
Mr. Horne said.
   Oil and construction companies, manufacturers, exporters
and distributors doing business with Iraq, Kuwait and other
nations in the region tend to buy coverage against such
political risks as an import/export embargo, expropriation or
nationalization of property. But political-risk insurance
generally doesn't cover property damage extending from any
conflict.
   Brokers and underwriters recall that the eight-year
Persian Gulf War cost insurers around the world several
billion dollars, including export guarantees. Marine insurers
alone paid out about $1 billion as a result of that war, the
brokers said.
   Lloyd's, firms in the London insurance market,
underwriters in a few other countries, such as France, and
some U.S. insurers, such as New York-based American
International Group Inc., provide the bulk of political-risk
and marine coverage.
   Maurice Greenberg, chairman and chief executive officer of
American International, said the company has little risk
exposure in the Persian Gulf region. "We have been involved
in the region for many years and we have managed our
exposures quite well. This {situation} will be no exception,"
he said.
   Lloyd's said its underwriters are currently charging an
additional premium of 0.025% of the insured value of ships
traveling in the Persian Gulf. That means owners of a ship
insured for $20 million, a typical value for a supertanker,
will pay $5,000 extra for two weeks' insurance coverage in
the region. Ship owners previously were paying about $10,000
for a full year's coverage.
   Rates can be significantly higher for ships going to
Kuwait, Iraq or northern ports in Saudi Arabia. Insurers are
charging $100,000 extra for a week of coverage in those
areas. Underwriters also are free to demand higher rates if
they judge the risks to be greater.
   Government agencies in the U.S., Britain and several other
European countries provide trade-related guarantees to
exporters.
   The U.S. Export-Import Bank, which provides coverage for
U.S. exporters and banks, has about $80 million to $100
million of potential exposure in Iraq from trade-guarantees
it has offered. However, some Ex-Im Bank guarantees might be
jeopardized by the U.S. government's embargo against Iraq.
Exposure in Kuwait is less than $10 million and about $15
million for Saudi Arabia, an agency official said. The agency
is reviewing its policies for Iraq and Kuwait.
   The Overseas Private Investment Corp., a U.S. agency that
insures companies investing in developing nations, said it
covers several projects in Kuwait, but declined to specify
the amount of its exposure. It does no business in Iraq. OPIC
is also active in Saudi Arabia, providing coverage for more
than 12 projects and with total exposure of about $40 million
to $50 million.
   The British Export Credits Guarantee Department, the
British counterpart of the Export-Import Bank, said it
stopped writing new business bound for Iraq in April, when
the Iraqis slid into a payment crisis and the agency started
to see claims. Sources believe that Britain's ECGD has
extended about $1 billion in trade-related guarantees to
Iraq, but the agency didn't confirm this amount.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
